<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38148c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38148c">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38148c"> 148(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> vox humana</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Can an instrument be constructed like the <i><mark>vox humana</mark></i> pipes of an organ, which shall accurately represent the sounds of a vowel? <small> Sir Richard Paget, <a name="RPHS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#RPHS"><cite title="source">Human Speech Some Observations &amp;c.</cite></a> (1930) 12 [section on &lsquo;Some Landmarks in Vocal Acoustics&rsquo;]</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Milesi adds: This passage is followed by a diagram on the five vowels, which could have helped foreground the theme at the end of the &ldquo;Mime&rdquo; and, as a later recall, in the &ldquo;Storiella&rdquo; section. </mm> </dd></dl>
